---
// A printable, shareable checklist for the writers' room. Static markup, no JS.
---
<div class="panel p-6 md:p-10 print:bg-white print:text-black">
  <p class="text-xs uppercase tracking-[0.25em] text-gold-400">Writers' Room Checklist</p>
  <h3 class="mt-1 font-display text-2xl text-white">
    10 questions to ask your script before greenlighting it.
  </h3>
  <p class="mt-3 text-sm text-white/60 max-w-2xl">
    Every scene encodes social norms about who deserves shame, who deserves
    pride, and who gets to decide. This checklist is a fast diagnostic for the
    writers' room: ten questions that surface the underlying assumptions of a
    scene before they harden into the final cut. Use it to test for unintended
    value judgements, find clichés worth subverting, and confirm that what's
    on the page is what you meant to say.
  </p>

  <ol class="mt-8 grid gap-3 md:grid-cols-2 text-sm leading-relaxed">
    <li class="rounded-lg bg-ink-950/40 ring-1 ring-white/5 px-4 py-3">
      <span class="font-display text-gold-400 text-xs">01.</span>
      <span class="ml-2 text-white/85">Who in the scene is feeling shame, and what triggered it?</span>
    </li>
    <li class="rounded-lg bg-ink-950/40 ring-1 ring-white/5 px-4 py-3">
      <span class="font-display text-gold-400 text-xs">02.</span>
      <span class="ml-2 text-white/85">Which characters feel pride and for what accomplishment?</span>
    </li>
    <li class="rounded-lg bg-ink-950/40 ring-1 ring-white/5 px-4 py-3">
      <span class="font-display text-gold-400 text-xs">03.</span>
      <span class="ml-2 text-white/85">If you flipped the gender of the characters, would the scene still work?</span>
    </li>
    <li class="rounded-lg bg-ink-950/40 ring-1 ring-white/5 px-4 py-3">
      <span class="font-display text-gold-400 text-xs">04.</span>
      <span class="ml-2 text-white/85">Is shame self-imposed, or is it being delivered by another character?</span>
    </li>
    <li class="rounded-lg bg-ink-950/40 ring-1 ring-white/5 px-4 py-3">
      <span class="font-display text-gold-400 text-xs">05.</span>
      <span class="ml-2 text-white/85">Does anyone in the scene refuse to be shamed? On what grounds?</span>
    </li>
    <li class="rounded-lg bg-ink-950/40 ring-1 ring-white/5 px-4 py-3">
      <span class="font-display text-gold-400 text-xs">06.</span>
      <span class="ml-2 text-white/85">If pride is being celebrated, is it for who someone <em>is</em> or what they <em>did</em>?</span>
    </li>
    <li class="rounded-lg bg-ink-950/40 ring-1 ring-white/5 px-4 py-3">
      <span class="font-display text-gold-400 text-xs">07.</span>
      <span class="ml-2 text-white/85">In scenes that depict pride or shame, are there any voices missing?</span>
    </li>
    <li class="rounded-lg bg-ink-950/40 ring-1 ring-white/5 px-4 py-3">
      <span class="font-display text-gold-400 text-xs">08.</span>
      <span class="ml-2 text-white/85">Have we seen this scene 100 times before? 1,000 times? Is that intentional?</span>
    </li>
    <li class="rounded-lg bg-ink-950/40 ring-1 ring-white/5 px-4 py-3">
      <span class="font-display text-gold-400 text-xs">09.</span>
      <span class="ml-2 text-white/85">If a 14-year-old watched only this scene, what would they learn was normal?</span>
    </li>
    <li class="rounded-lg bg-ink-950/40 ring-1 ring-white/5 px-4 py-3">
      <span class="font-display text-gold-400 text-xs">10.</span>
      <span class="ml-2 text-white/85">What line could you change to make the underlying assumption clear to the audience?</span>
    </li>
  </ol>

  <div class="mt-8 flex flex-wrap items-center gap-3 text-xs text-white/40">
    <button onclick="window.print()" class="rounded-full bg-white/5 px-4 py-2 text-white/70 ring-1 ring-white/10 hover:bg-white/10 hover:text-white transition print:hidden">
      Print this checklist
    </button>
    <span>or screenshot — it's CC-BY.</span>
  </div>
</div>
